the psychological cost of lying an experimental investigation siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr centers programs projects education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home research at siepr research project the psychological cost of lying an experimental investigation title the psychological cost of lying an experimental investigation principal investigator muriel niederle dates may 1 2008 march 31 2009 sponsor rsf my experiment will investigate the extent to which people are averse to deceiving other people a standard economic assumption is that people tell the truth only when it is selfishly advantageous to do so but recent work suggests otherwise in his experimental paper deception the role of consequences 2005 american economic review uri gneezy shows that subjects are more likely to make a selfish choice in a dictator game in which subjects choose monetary outcomes for themselves and other subjects than they are to lie to obtain that same selfish outcome in a different game involving messages in this sense gneezy shows that lying imposes a psychological cost for at least some people using gneezy's data and their own experiment hurkens and kartik 2006 cannot rule out the hypothesis that this cost is either zero or infinite my design will allow me to calculate this cost and i expect to show that most people experience non zero and finite psychological costs associated with lying stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
